David Saff wrote:

&gt; I can certainly see such a tool being helpful.  However, I would only 
&gt; have it report coverage failures if all the tests pass, I think.

   Thanks David. Both Hansel and my Cobertura hack do that already.

   regards,
   Eugene


&gt; Eugene Kuleshov wrote:
&gt; 
&gt;&gt;   I&#39;d like to hear opinions on the idea of raising test failures for
&gt;&gt; code not covered by tests right from the tests.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;   Consider simple class:
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;   public static class Foo {
&gt;&gt;     public void a() {
&gt;&gt;       System.err.println(&quot;Hellou!&quot;);
&gt;&gt;     }
&gt;&gt;   }
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;   with a typical junit test case (well, here are no assertions actually,
&gt;&gt; but that is not the point)
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;   public static class FooTest extends TestCase {
&gt;&gt;     public void testA() throws Exception {
&gt;&gt;       Foo s = new Foo();
&gt;&gt;       // s.a();
&gt;&gt;     }
&gt;&gt;   }
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;   So, one could wrap the above test case pointing to the classes under
&gt;&gt; test using special CoverageSuite:
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;   public static class FooTestCoverage {
&gt;&gt;     public static Test suite() {
&gt;&gt;       return new CoverageSuite(FooTest.class,
&gt;&gt;           new Class[] {Foo.class});
&gt;&gt;     }
&gt;&gt;   }
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; That would produce errors like this:
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; java.lang.RuntimeException: Line 30 is not covered
&gt;&gt;    at org.something.Foo.run(Foo.java:30)
&gt;&gt; ...
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;   These errors suppose to be raised for each uncovered conditional or
&gt;&gt; decision branch, which should give a good idea about newly added
&gt;&gt; untested code as well as somehow encourage to improve test coverage.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;   This is not a new idea and had been implemented in Hansel coverage
&gt;&gt; tool some time ago. I just implemented a prototype for Cobertura.
&gt;&gt;  
&gt;&gt;   regards,
&gt;&gt;   Eugene
